
Book: '''Tom Hodgkinson. How to be Idle. HarperCollins, 2005'''

'''The Idler movement on time and quality''':

“Travailler moins, produire plus.�? In other words, the less you work, the more you produce. And certainly in my own experience—even in the really good jobs—a lot of the day is just spent sitting there, staring at your screen, pretending to work, checking your emails, on the phone to your girlfriend. I realized I’d rather work hard for two or three hours in a day—which was the only real work I was doing—and then bobble about the rest of the time, in the park or whatever. I’ve found that there isn’t any correlation whatsoever between the hours put in and the quality of what comes out. Most of the Beatles’ songs probably originated in about five minutes. Often, the things that a lot of work has gone into have been incredibly bad because they’re over-worked."
(http://www.motherjones.com/arts/qa/2005/06/how_to_be_idle.html)

